    <!-- What is Bona Fide -->
    <section class="section" id="what-is">
      <h2>What Does "Bona Fide Marriage" Mean?</h2>
      <p>
        USCIS defines a <strong>bona fide marriage</strong> as one entered in good faith — meaning both spouses genuinely intended to establish a life together, not merely to obtain an immigration benefit. This standard applies to K-1 fiancé visa petitions (I-129F) and spousal visa petitions (I-130).
      </p>
      <p>
        The legal definition comes from the <strong>Immigration Marriage Fraud Amendments of 1986</strong>, which created the conditional green card system specifically to deter sham marriages. A fraudulent marriage — one entered solely for immigration purposes — is a federal crime carrying up to 5 years in prison and $250,000 in fines.
      </p>
      <div class="callout">
        <p><strong>Key distinction:</strong> USCIS isn't asking whether your marriage is happy or perfect. They're asking whether it's genuine — that both of you entered into it intending to build a shared life. Couples going through rough patches can still have a bona fide marriage.</p>
      </div>
      <p>
        The burden of proof is on the petitioner. You must affirmatively demonstrate the marriage is real — USCIS won't assume good faith. The more evidence you provide, the stronger your case.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- 4 Pillars -->
    <section class="section" id="pillars">
      <h2>The 4 Pillars of Bona Fide Marriage Evidence</h2>
      <p>Immigration officers evaluate four broad categories. A strong petition covers all four — weakness in any one area can trigger RFEs (Requests for Evidence) or even denial.</p>

      <div class="pillars-grid">
        <div class="pillar-card">
          <div class="pillar-num">Pillar 1</div>
          <h3>Financial Commingling</h3>
          <p>Evidence that you share money, property, or financial obligations — the strongest indicator of a shared life.</p>
          <ul class="pillar-examples">
            <li>Joint bank account statements</li>
            <li>Joint credit card or loan</li>
            <li>Co-signed lease or mortgage</li>
            <li>Joint tax returns (if married)</li>
            <li>Named as beneficiary on insurance/retirement</li>
            <li>Wire transfers between you</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="pillar-card">
          <div class="pillar-num">Pillar 2</div>
          <h3>Cohabitation</h3>
          <p>Evidence you have lived together or plan to share a home — shows you're building a real domestic life.</p>
          <ul class="pillar-examples">
            <li>Lease/mortgage with both names</li>
            <li>Utility bills at shared address</li>
            <li>Mail addressed to both at same address</li>
            <li>Property records showing joint ownership</li>
            <li>Rental agreement with both signatures</li>
            <li>Driver's license or ID at same address</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="pillar-card">
          <div class="pillar-num">Pillar 3</div>
          <h3>Children &amp; Family</h3>
          <p>Children from the relationship and integration into each other's family networks signal genuine commitment.</p>
          <ul class="pillar-examples">
            <li>Birth certificates naming both parents</li>
            <li>Photos with each other's family</li>
            <li>Communications with in-laws</li>
            <li>Family event invitations / attendance</li>
            <li>Support letters from family members</li>
            <li>Joint decisions about children</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="pillar-card">
          <div class="pillar-num">Pillar 4</div>
          <h3>Communication &amp; Visits</h3>
          <p>For long-distance couples, consistent communication and documented visits are the primary evidence of the relationship.</p>
          <ul class="pillar-examples">
            <li>Phone / video call logs</li>
            <li>Message thread screenshots (WhatsApp, iMessage)</li>
            <li>Flight boarding passes and passport stamps</li>
            <li>Hotel receipts or Airbnb bookings</li>
            <li>Travel photos with date/location data</li>
            <li>Gifts, flowers, money transfer records</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="callout">
        <p><strong>LDR note:</strong> If you haven't lived together yet (common for K-1 filers), lean heavily on Pillar 4. USCIS officers are familiar with long-distance international couples and will not penalize you for lack of cohabitation if you have strong communication and visit evidence.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

